            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "format": "text/html",
            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.IX.R1</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>The Word of a Gentleman.</strong></p>\n<p><span id=\"docs-internal-guid-64270040-7fff-3a06-a1fe-9ca62b17e250\">&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">This title appears in a darker ink than content notes directly below, suggesting that it was added separately. Indeed, the ink used for this chapter title is a similar darkness to that used for the final chapter note, &ldquo;The word of a gentleman,&ndash;he will certainly keep it&rdquo; (LD.IX.R4). In the manuscript, the title is squeezed in between the header and the text as if added later. Given the imperatives in the opening notation (&ldquo;Pursue Rigaud,&rdquo; &ldquo;Suspend it all&rdquo;), we could speculate that Dickens may have written these first chapter notes (up to &ldquo;Scene in Mrs Clennam&rsquo;s room&rdquo;) proactively before composing the bulk of the chapter, leaving a space in the Note for the title, which he could have settled on when adding the final chapter note and writing the closing scene, which uses this same language.</p>"
        }
